---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout title="The Kill Chain Comes Home">
  <div class="content">
    <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(157, 78, 221, 0.2); color: #9D4EDD;">The Thesis</span>
    <h1>The Kill Chain Comes Home</h1>
    <p class="subtitle" style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: 1.15rem;">
      The same company builds the software that targets a drone strike abroad and the software that tracks a deportation at home. The tools are tested on people with the least power to refuse, then they move inward. The local camera is the newest node.
    </p>

    <h2>One Company, Two Ends of the Same Machine</h2>
    <p>
      Palantir was founded in 2003 with CIA venture funding (In-Q-Tel) and is chaired by billionaire Peter Thiel, a major financial backer of the current administration and mentor to the vice president. It builds the data backbone for operations that look unrelated and turn out to be one architecture.
    </p>

    <div class="card">
      <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(157, 78, 221, 0.2); color: #9D4EDD;">Abroad &middot; Targeting</span>
      <h3>Project Maven (Pentagon)</h3>
      <p>Maven is the Pentagon's AI targeting system, using satellite imagery, drone footage, and predictive algorithms to automate the "kill chain": find, fix, track, target, engage, assess.</p>
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li>Contract grew from <strong>$480 million into the billions</strong></li>
        <li>Pentagon staff used Maven to help <strong>pick targets in the US strikes on Iran</strong></li>
        <li>Palantir CEO Alex Karp: "our weapons software is in every combat situation I'm aware of"</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="source">Sources: Liberation News (2025); Davis Vanguard (2025); AFSC Investigate.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(157, 78, 221, 0.2); color: #9D4EDD;">At Home &middot; Deportation</span>
      <h3>ImmigrationOS (ICE)</h3>
      <p>The same company's ICE platform, a roughly $30 million contract, fuses license plates, Medicaid records, and travel data to give the agency "near real-time visibility" into people's movements.</p>
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li>Assigns a <strong>"confidence score"</strong> and a map pin for arrest</li>
        <li>ICE-Palantir contracts total <strong>$435M+ since 2011</strong></li>
        <li>Palantir's tools raised ICE's target-location rate from ~27% to nearly <strong>80%</strong></li>
        <li>A linked tool, ELITE, taps <strong>Medicaid data</strong> to locate arrest targets</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="source">Sources: ACLU (Apr 2026); Fortune (Jan 2026); American Immigration Council; AFSC Investigate.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Where the Tools Are Tested First</h2>
    <p>
      The pattern is consistent: surveillance and targeting systems are deployed first against the people with the least power to refuse, then normalized and turned inward.
    </p>

    <div class="card">
      <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(244, 67, 54, 0.2); color: #F44336;">Palestine</span>
      <h3>The UN Named Palantir Directly</h3>
      <p>This is not an accusation we're inventing. The UN's own human rights office published it.</p>
      <p>
        On June 30, 2025, UN Special Rapporteur Francesca Albanese released the report <em>"From Economy of Occupation to Economy of Genocide."</em> It names <strong>Palantir specifically</strong>, finding reasonable grounds to believe the company provided predictive-policing technology, core military software infrastructure, and its AI Platform enabling <strong>real-time battlefield data integration for automated decision-making</strong> to the Israeli military, a relationship that predates October 2023.
      </p>
      <p>
        Palantir's CEO publicly dismissed the complicity allegations by saying its technology had helped kill "mostly terrorists", a remark the Rapporteur cited as evidence of executive-level knowledge. The US government then sanctioned Albanese for the report; the UN called that a dangerous precedent.
      </p>
      <p class="source">Sources: OHCHR press release (July 2025); UN report A/HRC/59/23, "From Economy of Occupation to Economy of Genocide"; Middle East Eye; Al Jazeera; AOAV.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(244, 162, 97, 0.2); color: #F4A261;">Immigrants</span>
      <h3>Then the Deportation Machine</h3>
      <p>The same predictive architecture that processes battlefield targets processes deportation targets. Palantir has been ICE's core data partner since 2011, under Obama, Biden, and Trump alike. The American Immigration Council's point is the sharp one: when a system decides which data triggers an alert, <strong>the architecture itself becomes policy.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(230, 57, 70, 0.2); color: #E63946;">And Now, Dissent</span>
      <h3>The Enemies List Is Written Down</h3>
      <p>In September 2025 the administration signed <strong>NSPM-7</strong>, which brands "anti-fascism" as a cover for terrorism and lists <strong>"anti-capitalism"</strong> and "anti-Christianity" as indicators of extremism. Not actions, beliefs. The May 2026 Counterterrorism Strategy named "Anti-Fascists" as a top domestic threat category. The same month, EFF records showed Arizona agencies had already used Flock to run searches tied to anti-administration protests.</p>
      <p class="source">Sources: White House (Sept 25, 2025); Brennan Center; ACLU; TIME; EFF.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>The Local Connection</h2>
    <p>
      You can't unplug Palantir from Safford. But the on-ramp is here. Flock's data platform can integrate with predictive-policing systems including Palantir, and the cameras on our roads feed a national network. The plate reader, the dossier, the confidence score, the kill chain, it's one architecture, built to integrate every database into a single searchable interface.
    </p>
    <p>
      A government that writes "anti-fascist" and "anti-capitalist" into a terror directive, plus a surveillance network that already logged who drove to a protest, is the combination worth naming out loud. The machine was built pointed outward. It is turning around.
    </p>

    <h2>How To Talk About This Honestly</h2>
    <p>
      We hold a hard line on sourcing here, because the strongest version of this argument is the documented one. The Palestine connection rests on the <strong>UN's own published report</strong> and the material relationship it names, not on anyone's identity or ancestry. Criticizing a company's contracts and a government's policy is ordinary politics. We keep it there, and so should you.
    </p>

    <div class="cta-banner">
      <h3>The Front Door Is on Your Street</h3>
      <p>You can ask who has been searching the cameras in Graham County, and you can join the people organizing against them.</p>
      <a href={`${base}records/`} class="btn">Take Action</a>
      <a href={`${base}petition/`} class="btn btn-outline">Sign the Petition</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
